We were also curious as to how the inserted passages will hit, in which the main hero will get out of the car and run his way.
But as with the NFS series, a lot of it is a little different than we expected.
They are potentially decent arcade racing, but the whole thing pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have appeared in the series more or less over the years.
So it's actually not a mistake, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are featured in a story whose main character Jack has certain personal problems and as a solution offers to participate in an illegal race across America.
Behind the wheel you sit on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea carries with it a number of interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
As a result, each race runs on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
It doesn’t feel like the game is always the same.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing universal.
But riding across the desert, in the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains is visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are occasionally sprayed with some non-typical element.
In the desert, for example, you get stuck in a sandstorm, which greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you need to be careful not to fall asleep avalanche.
In addition, individual races are set up quite well behind each other.
There are only a few types, but that is enough.
For a moment you try to pass the required number of opponents (essentially a classic race), then you get time again (classic fight with the tracks) and then you need a duel with a single opponent.
In addition, from time to time, you will also get involved with the police, which further upsets all your efforts.
There are new passages outside the car.
Rather, it’s just an interactive animation where Jack usually flies in front of someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right times.
Nothing complicated.
However, it will come as a surprise that these passages are in the game much less than you would expect (in particular, maybe even just three).
As a result, however, this is for the benefit of the thing, because this element does not have a chance to become annoying and in the context of the above, it thus ranks among the elements that spoil the game.
The riding model follows in the footsteps of previous parts.
That means it’s definitely not a lot of people these days, but it can’t be said that it would be an opposition.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more accurately conceived race here, the riding model still fits quite well, even though we would be able to find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
But the problems begin to arise after a while.
In contrast to the driving model, the model is no longer very good.
From a game of this type, we do not expect that it counts complex deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea how your car is maintained before practically any impact on any object, then it is probably not all right.
Typically, when driving in close traffic or driving a car in normal traffic, you’ll sometimes just lick each other slightly, but sometimes in an almost identical situation, your car will end up in wild pirouettes.
Or even just think about it.
Thanks to the restart system, it does not matter at all, but it will make you feel more comfortable.
Restarts are arranged so that if you break up or go far off the track, the game throws you back to the last catch point on the track.
However, there are only five restarts available in each race.
When you run out of them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it’s more of a tool in case something goes wrong than you could rely on it explicitly.
Sometimes, however, even restarts will not help, it will solve them until the need to learn to remember a given section of the race.
The big downside of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, require a project in a specific way, otherwise you will not get into them briefly.
Other times, you will meet the "civil" cars at a given location always in the same configuration, whether you come there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see a competitor passing easily between two opposing cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive or brake them.
It doesn’t matter when you get to them, because it’s “calculated” so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Competitors also have another advantage.
Throughout the game you will encounter several places where you, again, no matter the time, will always precede the same opponent in the same place.
Most of all, it pigs at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
The opponent must get there in front of you, apparently, at any cost.
When it goes in front of you, it makes you worse at the overview of the opposing cars, so you get a good massage there a couple of times in the beginning.
You may understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-fueled, but the implementation is so obvious that it will reliably dissipate you quickly.
And it’s a shame, because despite the simple riding model is playing fun and places even so action that sometimes you literally can’t keep track of where it’s flying.
And it really doesn’t matter whether it deserves a concept with fifty unique tracks, ranking races so that boredom doesn’t have a chance, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to exchange cars during races.
You need to pay attention to the petrol pumps on the road, because there you can change the car, although in most cases you’ll get enough of what you just have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Athletes are suitable for urban areas, strong American storms on straight highways and exotic supersports on technical rides, for example on clicked mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand and challenge mode, which are races in the individual locations you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points to your profile, which is common for challenges and story.
To obtain a higher level of driver, different objects are unlocked: starting cars and ending with backgrounds for the profile.
At the same time, it is again connected to the online Autolog feature, which among other things compares your achieved results with other players and provides other community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand puzzles is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you can get to the metro tunnel (Budzh), where you will marry in the dark by rail (Budzh).
On the tachometer you can see numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (Budzh) and in the back there is a set of meters and uncompromisingly upset you.
In the editorial board, we will probably have a few more days to discuss whether no one really thought a bit when creating the game, or whether the authors have us as such a big idiot.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It freezes so that in some quieter moments, the shooting decreases, and in some cases, quite tragically.
However, this is especially the case with a larger number of participants, when you no longer have anything to do with the smooth shooting.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an attempt to please the widest possible range of the younger audience, a soundtrack of the category "every dog is different all" was created, but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, probably no one will buy the game.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is very disappointing.
If the game were to make absolutely unnecessary mistakes, then we wouldn’t be afraid to say that The Run is the best piece of NFS in the last few years.
But that’s how the game works.
The fun is definitely great, but be prepared to make sure that your mistakes will be shaken in the eyes by the power of airport spotlights.
