How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel offices were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time were mostly only selling trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled on holiday to the sea to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime acceded to the West and the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia was subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or to the Soviet Union, then he needed a letter of summons from this country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand out from the front overnight with a sleeper or to have "good friends" in the travel office.
However, it was not won either.
The so-called currency pledge, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a currency pledge it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) on the way to the West.
However, by far the Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of chats and chalets that the Czechs acquired and this habit survives to this day.
Since 1989, the Czech Republic has been experiencing a real revolution.
While until 1989, holidays in the NDR or Bulgaria were our top priority, the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the most popular Croatia until 1989, as it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
As early as the late 1990s, visa obligations to neighbouring Western European countries were lifted, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria, Vienna or Germany.
The Czechs could not afford to travel to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czechs’ trips to parks burned in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of travelling the Czechs during this time was to drive their own food, canned food, salads, etc., to be saved.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally freely buy Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with it average wages have increased, which led to another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare charter flights since 1997, which has led to an incredible reduction in air travel, thanks to the possibility of contracting numerous discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free access to virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the United States, which made it easier for us to travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in the year 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight into exoticism was sent from the Czech Republic, it was to Thailand.
From this year onwards, Czech tourists fly direct charters to warm distant countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting around 100,000 Czechs per year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. revoked a visa for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) for the first time in history and spent more than CZK 15 thousand per person for one holiday abroad, including on-site costs.
