The new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that keeps the country above the brink of economic disaster.
The appointed Prime Minister of Italy, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to present him with a new government that will face a crisis that keeps the country above the collapse of the economic disaster that has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The presidential palace issued a report in which it announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgi Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
It is expected to introduce a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to create a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well marked," he added.
Monti completed the process of creating a government in less than three days, i.e. in a much shorter time than usual, while Italy is trying to fight the political and financial crisis, which led the debt level to an unsustainable level.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Montim, must approve a tough package of austerity measures demanded by European leaders, the only way it will be possible to restore Italy’s entrenched credibility.
Due to market instability, interest rates from Italian BTP bonds with a ten-year maturity of 7 per cent have exceeded the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for a bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of Confindustria’s Italian employers’ organisation, told reporters after a meeting with Montim: “We said we would support this government very much.”
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this dire situation.
Monti’s hopes for success have increased significantly thanks to the support of PDL Silvia Berlusconi, whose crisis forced her to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined for good results," Angelina Alfano, the secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant, because until now a number of its members have stood up against the government with a technocratic majority, which Monti assembles.
Parliament's support
The new Monti government must have strong support from Parliament in order to promote unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in this effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks has joined the pressure and warns that Monti’s failure could be a disaster.
Monti began talks on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women’s organisations.
The round of talks will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, who enabled a very rapid process in response to the crisis.
After a brief decline at the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi was resigning, the interest rates of Italian bondholders returned to the critical border, reacting to uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister was successful.
To save Italy, whose public debt is <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.8 trillion, would be beyond the scope of the eurozone’s current financial reserves.
Monti said his government should remain in power until the next elections, which are scheduled for 2013, despite the general forecast, which he says give politicians time only to carry out reforms, and then announce early elections.
Monti said he would like to incorporate policies into his cabinet, but the big parties insist that this government must be composed only of experts to bring Italy out of the difficulties the country has come to due to financial pressure.
Political sources have said that bilateral mistrust and disagreement between the parties complicates the attempt to incorporate both government and political personality into the government.
