Quintet included the country in its tour on the occasion of the celebration of 20 years of existence
“The road to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality.”
In an exclusive interview for Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that for them the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This is what the bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, who spoke exclusively to Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate 20 years of existence and will be on Sunday 20th at a unique stopover in Central America.
This day will be performed from 7:30 p.m. at the National Stadium along with the Angel group The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is an example of an interview whose entire transcript can be found on La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n's website.
For your Costa Rican fan, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The road to Costa Rica is also our dream, which is becoming a reality.
In South and Central America we are barely the second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, it's a wonderful country, and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we're so happy to be able to bring you our music.
I ask myself, because they love the group here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensively.
What do you say to your biggest fans?
Thank you for staying with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long.
Some people talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve shown in the last 21 years have been on the horizon for several weeks.
We have performed several great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that this will allow us to get into the form of a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to the concert.
We love this country, we like to surf, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of friends of surfers and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. And so we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
When we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we don't have any restrictions on what we can't do.
We will try to present the best show with different songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and varied repertoire.
You will never repeat the repertoire.
Why?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs we’ll play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played in a long time, we focus on them and we’re also surprised because we’ll remember why we liked them so much and that we might have forgotten about it already.
So the show is more interesting for us, and that’s why I think it’s more interesting for people as well.
This tour celebrates 20 years of the art track.
When you look back, it’s hard to believe everything you’ve ever done.
Yes, that's for sure.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we'd be in a big rock band and that we'd be staying in it for more than 20 years.
We realize how much has been given to us and we feel that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to be able to look at the places we have always longed for.
We couldn't have gotten any better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group in which the greats themselves are represented.
People from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It is surprising that when the movement arises from a group of friends, too often it does not happen.
From time to time a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud of it and are honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with some of them.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored that we can be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It’s also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after those years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which by itself is much longer than the usual duration of the band.
I think the first time we are all lucky, we are still in this world and the second time our role is played by the fact that we are constantly interested in each other.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open up musical pathways that leave everyone with enough freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we value each other's music, and I don't think it could be any better.
Your relationship to the word of fame has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it was increasingly easier to find a balance.
We try not to ride too much on tour because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people have come for music, you will remember that you have to respect music and what you have given to it. You must not let yourself be carried away by being famous, rock stars. This has never really been of any interest to any of us.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs and at the beginning it was something great.
We’ve been a band for three years and we’ve never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating, because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we still make friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us. When I would listen to a song or watch a movie, I would laugh at it
He was an incredible person and we miss him very much.
The Las Robertas National Band will be tasked with launching the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that that's why you chose them as your forerunners?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most. That's why we're curious what Las Robertas will offer live and they have to be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
A lot of people.
Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I could talk all night about the basics that I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've all always felt a slight separation from the word grunge.
When I say grunge, I imagine the bands that I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. And if music is still valid today, then it's something great, because it's the music that makes the band stand out and it's the music that makes it sound so loud
At first, your music had a slightly cloudy character and is now more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter to burn, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very cloudy, although they may sound positive.
At both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried, and they're songs deep in the dark.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from a family or a friend, these things will start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent just that to me.
I also think that you can be a happy person and still make cloudy music.
