Mexico’s Institute of Health Insurance has launched a gene research that causes obesity.
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to reveal genes that cause obesity in children and young people. A study called "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Youths" will allow you to get results related to overweight.
In a report, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Research Medical Unit in Biochemistry at the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 21st Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team relies on the support of specialists and students of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research can also be undertaken by a wide audience, with or without permission. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where they will run tests for young people every 8 hours.
He stressed that the research started at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexico) and since October 8 this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Centre (East of Mexico).
As soon as data from 500 to 600 children is obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and significance of genetics when it comes to the development of obesity, and to identify risk factors for Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on balance.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and the family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He pointed out that every Saturday with all participants, anthropometric measurements are carried out (weight, height, circumference of the waist), blood pressure is measured, the level of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin is determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes, try to identify genes).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said this research reflects the concern of physicians over alarming increases in children’s weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was only a 77% increase in obesity among boys and a 47% increase in girls. There was also a dramatic increase in overweight," said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the country's population differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% of European and 5% of African. This fact is reflected in genes that are responsible for the emergence of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is usually explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) that is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of participants is that they will receive an overall assessment of the child’s condition, which will determine whether they are experiencing any known overweight or obesity.
He noted that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and precancerous conditions.
The information is confidential so far, doctors pass it on in writing to the parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes that they need to make to prevent their children from getting the disease.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life that means a lack of daily physical activity, a full-day sitting in front of the TV, and the use of means of transport instead of space.
Excessive weight is also caused by high caloric intake, this is the greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no excuses in Asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climate conditions and temperature
If properly cared for irrigation, there would be no need to repair almost 200,000 landslides after each period of rainfall in the Valle de México metropolitan area, warned Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) from UNAM, who would have been building a dam, and would have survived until the end.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Extinction, which he presented during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should create a mixture having similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time it is growing from the same time.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, for example in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the formation of effluents.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a high molecular weight, which are called asphaltenes, and others with a low molecular weight, which are called maltenes.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures, asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day depending on weather conditions and temperature, the expert on chemical engineering pointed out.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with a flexible slab made up of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers is an asphalt insert, formed by small stones poured into the asphalt and then pressed.
He stressed that every stone that makes up the insert is filled with asphalt.
When passing the car or when creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the tile to be well distributed.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, according to a chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer called a layer, made of fine stone, i.e. sand, also poured into the asphalt, will be placed on the asphalt insert.
Since this layer will come into contact with the vehicle sheaths, it must have a greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the carriage.
Since as part of the rigging will be exposed to a large load, the garment must have a sufficient thickness and must pay attention to the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the ground is wet, the water spreads inside and it is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the tile and thus the emergence of wrinkles.
He explained that during the creation of the molds, the film of the coating will be destroyed first and only then damage to the asphalt insert occurs. However, the damage does not occur at one point, but it is a slow process that should be stopped already at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of bulges, and therefore the thickness of each layer of tiles must correspond to the load of vehicles and must ensure that this load can not exceed the load.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that when it comes to asphalt, a lot of work is still waiting for us and research is at the beginning. For example, there are asphalt emulsions, which are already available in other countries on the market and allow us to easily repair molds without having to use them.
