The Nord Stream long-distance gas pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and led to the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to function.
They must supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday’s inauguration of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together to control the valve that controls Russian gas entering the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe each year with the first pipeline of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Commonwealth of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
The second pipeline, to be completed at the end of 2012, will allow a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas to be delivered, which is an amount equal to the entire French consumption.
And it is already possible to build a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the early completion of this huge building is a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested against the project.
Nord Stream will in fact be able to deliver gas directly to Germany without being driven across the country by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At times, these two countries are losing their power somewhat: the possibility of pressing Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets becomes more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not dare to compare the Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
That is to say, it is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, with its support for this Russian project, has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, as the project has created gaps between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Just five years ago, Russia succeeded in pursuing its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries with high gas consumption, the bearings of which are nearing their end.
“This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new pipeline that organically connects us,” Fillon said at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom’s leading representatives present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas port.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an important technical step.
The subsea pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete cladding to be protected from the anchors of marine vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“For their safety, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted anywhere by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but it was rejected by the project manager, when the Swedes were only reluctant to see Russian state society continue to sit on their shores.
“In the event of a failure, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute,” explains Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In case of gas tightness contained in the gas duct, it escapes into the air.
But this case is considered to be unlikely to the builder, because the shafts were designed so that the impermanence occurred once every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline is controlled from the outside by an underwater robot drawn by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This tobacco-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the pipe and is pressed by gas.
The target will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts over the entire three-day journey at a speed of 3 m/s.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any minor repairs.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the target.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom remains in the lead, holding a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in the city of Zoug in Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased all of its gas transport capacity to Gazprom for a five-year contract that could be renewed.
“Gazprom will benefit from the overall capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported in any way,” explains Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% of the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipes.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline comes from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves at a height of 4.5 meters form a gas outlet.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When the full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
