Why is there such a high proportion of unemployable handicapped workers?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today is the 15th week for hiring handicapped people.
Despite the voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed people with disabilities is still two times higher than the average, i.e. 19% versus 9% for the entire population.
Is it cluttering?
"No, underscores <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, which organizes the Week for the Employment of Persons with Disabilities."
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At the time, the percentage of the unemployed was not twice as high, but three times as high."
"But there's still a lot to do."
It must be said that for the unemployed people with disabilities, there are numerous obstacles to their entry into work.
These are older people: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% have no maturities and out of 2.3 million high school students, only 10,000 are handicapped.
And finally - long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% of people with disabilities versus 38% on average.
In short, such are the criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to employment and which represent the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, general manager of the Tremplin Association, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses accept handicapped workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
It remains unspoken, ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
The study, conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association, found that the managers questioned had a “low level of knowledge about handicapped people” with an “overwhelming view of people in wheelchairs and mental or mental disabilities”.
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the goal of employing 6% of the disabled workers laid down in the 1987 Act.
The last known figures, which come from 2008, indicate a level of 2.6%.
“We are now moving about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, which is responsible for collecting fees from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence is the number of "punished" enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 guilty enterprises between 2007 and 2011 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ handicapped workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
